Banks to tackle crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the crisis in the financial markets together.
This will bring more than $100 billion to the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, the banks are auctioning off the interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
The US Fed, for example, will send forty billion dollars to auction, and another twenty-four will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time following the attacks of September 11th that national central banks have agreed to take such coordinated action to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This move is to address the economy's biggest difficulties, a growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
"The coordinated action of the central banks reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to as much as fifty percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion in defaulted loans, mainly in the United States.
Analysts expect even more billions in losses.
"Central banks must really be afraid of what may yet follow when they opted for this course of action," said ABN's chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to the loans, they will also lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the US economy into recession with the potential effects on the world's economic growth.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate, which is used for borrowing money in the interbank market.
This meant that the banks were still concerned about borrowing each other, even though the US, Canada, and Britain's central banks had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that central banks' move will contribute to the crisis's upright because it does not address the underlying problem, and that is the collapse of the US housing market.
